<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaves for Summit With Clinton </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002104494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1025 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002104494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 10 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa left for Washington on Thursday [10 February] for a 
summit meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton, which is 
expected to focus on stalled trade negotiations. 
  Hosokawa and wife Kayoko, who departed on a government 
aircraft from Haneda Airport, are scheduled to arrive in 
Washington later Thursday evening local time. 
  The prime minister will meet with Clinton for two hours 
Friday in an effort to break the deadlock over trade issues. 
  He is also scheduled to attend a joint press conference with 
Clinton, meet with leaders of the Republican Party, and deliver 
a speech in English at Clinton's alma mater, Georgetown 
University. 
  Hosokawa is scheduled to return to Japan on Sunday. 
  It will be the third meeting between the two leaders, but 
Clinton is expected to press Hosokawa harder this time for a 
"results-oriented" agreement on the bilateral trade framework 
negotiations. 

</TEXT>

