<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Arrives in Washington To Discuss Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002015694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0133 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002015694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, Feb. 9 KYODO -- Japanese Deputy Prime 
Minister and Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata arrived in Washington 
on Wednesday [9 February] night to try to break a deadlock in 
the stalled framework trade talks between Japan and the United 
States. 
  U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor earlier in the day 
announced the suspension of working-level negotiations until 
Hata's arrival in the hope that a Japanese political decision 
could lead to a breakthrough. 
  The talks, which had resumed in Washington early this week, 
stalled due to a squabble over how to measure Japan's efforts to 
open its auto and other markets. 
  Hata is to join Friday's summit meeting between Prime 
minister Morihiro Hosokawa and President Bill Clinton. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

