<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets With Kantor 10 Feb Morning </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002125294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1233 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002125294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Washington, Feb. 10 KYODO -- Japan's Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata met Thursday morning [10 February] with 
U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor in a bid to break the 
deadlock in the stalled bilateral framework trade talks before 
Friday's Japan-U.S. Summit. 
  The meeting was held as Japan and the United States head 
toward a showdown over a plethora of trade issues before Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and President Bill Clinton meet. 
Hata arrived in Washington late Wednesday on an emergency 
mission seeking U.S. understanding on the Japanese position. 
  Hata said he is bringing no new proposals to Washington. 
  Japan has turned down a U.S. demand that numerical targets 
be 
set to measure the progress in opening Japan's markets, saying 
they would result in managed trade. [passage omitted] 

