<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Suggests Partial Accord for Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002035094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0342 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002035094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 10 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
should not let the trade "framework" talks collapse and a 
partial agreement should be sought if necessary, Japan's trade 
minister said Thursday [10 February]. 
  "The U.S. has lately stiffened its attitude to seek numeral 
targets in the talks, because the talks are reaching a crucial 
point," said Hiroshi Kumagai, minister of international trade 
and industry, [MITI] after the day's ad hoc cabinet meeting. 
  Japan, for its part, remains opposed to introducing such 
"numerical" targets to measure progress in opening Japan's 
markets, he said. 
  "But I believe we cannot afford to cancel everything we have 
discussed in the talks," Kumagai said, adding the two countries 
should agree on whatever issues they could. 
  Areas for such partial agreement include simplifying Japan's 
government procurement procedures and increasing private-level 
cooperation programs in the respective automotive industries, he 
suggested. 
  He also said the two countries have discussed in 
working-level negotiations including in the final accord the 
opinions of two sides about the numeral targets. 
  Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa is scheduled to 
leave Thursday for Washington to review progress in the 
framework talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton on Friday. 

</TEXT>

