<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russians Reportedly Detain 2 Fishing Boats </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002145294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1440 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002145294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kushiro, Hokkaido, Feb. 10 KYODO -- A Russian 
vessel forced two Japanese fishing boats to undergo inspections 
and one of them has not yet returned, Maritime Safety Agency 
officials said Thursday [10 February]. 
  The Russian vessel, apparently a patrol boat, forced the 
83rd 
Kintoku Maru and the 18th Tenyu Maru to stop on Wednesday 
morning as they were sailing in waters 20 kilometers south of 
Etorofu, one of the four disputed islands held by Russia. The 
two trawlers were taken to Shikotan, also one of the four 
Russian-held and Japanese-claimed islands, and underwent 
inspection by Russian authorities, they said. 
  The Tenyu Maru with a crew of 16, based in Ishinomaki, 
Miyagi 
Prefecture, was released later that day and returned to Kushiro 
on Thursday morning but the whereabouts of the Kintoku Maru also 
with 16 crew members from Kushiro is still not known, the 
officials said. The Kintoku Maru and its crew are believed to 
be detained there, the officials said. 
  The two vessels had been engaged in fishing operations south 
of the Kuril chain of islands under a fishing agreement between 
Japan and Russia. Disputes over sovereignty of the four islands 
-- Kunashiri, Etorofu, Shikotan and the Habomai groups of islets 
-- have marred relations between the two countries. 

</TEXT>

