<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Main Points' of Draft Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002090094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0850 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002090094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 10 KYODO -- The following are the main 
points of the fiscal 1994 budget proposed Thursday by the 
Finance Ministry. 
  -- The budget allocates a mere 1.0 percent rise in the 
general accounts from the initial fiscal 1993 budget. Without 
technical accounting factors, the budget will post the first 
year-to-year contraction in 39 years. 
  -- The Finance Ministry plans to issue deficit-coverning 
bonds for the first time in five years to make up for revenue 
shortfalls stemming mainly from 6 trillion yen tax cuts. The 
ministry also plans to issue more construction bonds. As a 
result, the ratio of dependence on public borrowings rises to 
18.7 percent from 11.2 percent in fiscal 1993. 
  -- The general operating expenditures will rise only 2.3 
percent but public works-related outlays will rise a relatively 
high 4.0 percent. 
  -- Defense spending is up 0.8 percent for the lowest rise 
since fiscal 1960 and official development assistance (ODA) will 
rise 4.0 percent. 
  -- The draft fiscal investment and loan program allocates 
7.0 
percent higher outlays to finance housing, public works and 
other projects. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

