<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Business Chiefs Criticize Draft </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002113794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1112 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002113794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 10 KYODO -- Some Japanese business 
leaders Thursday [10 February] criticized the 73.08 trillion yen 
draft budget unveiled by the Finance Ministry. 
  Takeshi Nagano, president of the Japan Federation of 
Employers Associations (Nikkeiren), said it contains few new 
elements. The draft should have included more of the original 
policy objectives of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, 
especially in seeking a higher quality of living for Japanese, 
he said. 
  Nagano suggested that spending should have been expanded to 
reform the nation's industrial structure, such as providing 
appropriations for agriculture. 
  Masaru Hayami, chairman of the Japan Association of 
Corporate 
Executives (Keizai Doyukai), said drastic cuts in expenditures 
should be sought through a complete review of outlays for 
individual ministries and agencies. 
  Kosaku Inaba, chairman of the Japan Chamber of Commerce and 
Industry, urged the government to strictly check expenditures in 
implementing the budget. But Inaba welcomed an increase of more 
than 4 percent in the proposed public works spending for its 
economic stimulation effects. 

</TEXT>

