<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Draft Draws LDP, JCP Criticism </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002150194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1436 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002150194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 10 KYODO -- Top policy-makers of the 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and the Japanese Communist Party 
(JCP) on Thursday [10 February] criticized the 73.08 trillion 
yen draft budget compiled and made public by the Finance 
Ministry. 
  Ryutaro Hashimoto, chairman of the LDP Policy Affairs 
Research Council, said the draft shows that the issue of a 
budget for construction of new bullet train lines and other 
difficult problems has been sidestepped and left unsettled. The 
chief LDP policy-maker said his party will press the government 
in the Diet to meet its budget demands. 
  Noriaki Sasaki, chairman of the JCP Economic Policy 
Committee, said it is unacceptable that the budget limits income 
tax cuts to one year. He said the draft shows that if income 
tax cuts are to be on a permanent basis, there would have to be 
a major raise in the consumption tax rate and such an increase 
is quite unacceptable. 

</TEXT>

