<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Accord To Abolish Tax on Firms' Share Purchases </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002044494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0510 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002044494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 9 KYODO -- The Japanese Government and 
the ruling coalition have decided to abolish the current system 
of imposing taxes on companies buying their own shares and 
writing them off, officials said Wednesday [9 February]. 
  Under the current system, a per-share capital increase 
resulting from a company's purchases of its own shares for 
write-offs is regarded as a taxable dividend. 
  The business community and securities companies have been 
calling for abolition of the tax to make it easier for companies 
to buy their own shares. 
  The officials said the system will be abolished under a 
fiscal 1994 tax reform program and in connection with the 
scheduled year-end lifting of restrictions on companies buying 
their own shares. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

