<H3> <TI>   MITI's New Industrial Policy Chief Chosen </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002140694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1318 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 10 KYODO -- Tomio Tsutsumi, director 
general of the Natural Resources and Energy Agency, has been 
selected Industrial Policy Bureau director general at the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI), ministry 
officials said Thursday [10 February]. 
  Tsutsumi, chosen by Trade Minister Hiroshi Kumagai, will be 
appointed to the post on approval at a cabinet meeting Tuesday, 
the officials said. 
  Masahisa Naito resigned from the post in December following 
charges of favoritism in promoting a junior while he served as 
director general at the MITI minister's secretariat. 
  In December 1992, Naito promoted Yasufumi Tanahashi, son of 
a 
former vice trade minister, to the hurriedly created post of 
planning officer shortly before Tanahashi quit the ministry to 
run in the House of Representatives election in July 1993. 
  MITI Vice Minister Hideaki Kumano has been concurrently 
serving as the Industrial Policy Bureau chief since Naito 
resigned. 

</TEXT>

