<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministries Said Divided on Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1102014994 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 10 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 11--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1102014994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Haruyuki Aikawa] </F>
  [Text] Washington, 8 Feb -- Whether an accord can be 
reached at the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks now hinges on 
which side will compromise on the numerical target issue. So 
far, neither has made any moves toward compromise. However, 
some members of the Japanese group engaged in negotiations in 
Washington have begun to share a need for concession. Thus, 
hard-line officials -- mainly from the Ministry of Finance and 
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry -- have once 
again called for caution and warned the Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs against giving too much consideration to the United 
States. 
  Regarding the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks, a 
diplomatic source in the United States said: "If the talks 
should break down, our efforts accumulated so far will go down 
the drain, and such a situation must be avoided." In this way, 
he maintained that due consideration should be given to the 
United States. His comments indicate that Japan should make 
concessions because the U.S. Congress is now moving toward 
submitting a bill on retaliatory measures against Japan. At 
the same time, the same source was also aware that the views of 
Japanese hard-liners must be taken into consideration, and said: 
"I am not saying that Japan should make unreasonable 
compromises. But what is important is that the talks must be 
brought to an appropriate settlement." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

