<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Rejects Clinton Remark on Exchange Rate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1302120794 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 Feb 
94 Evening Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1302120794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Clinton reportedly said on 11 February 
that foreign exchange rates will be included in the "objective 
criteria," designed to measure Japan's progress in liberalizing 
its market. In this regard, the Japanese Government and the 
Bank of Japan [BOJ] are strongly denying the possibility of 
introducing the objective criteria, saying: "The exchange rate 
should be determined according to the fundamentals (basic 
economic conditions) and the U.S. monetary authorities share the 
same idea." Saying that "we will fulfill our role as the 
monetary authorities if the exchange rate significantly responds 
to political factors," the BOJ is prepared to intervene in the 
market by selling yen and buying dollars should the value of the 
yen increase further at the Tokyo Foreign Exchange market. 
  Regarding the President's remark, the BOJ points out that 
the 
President "merely explained a general view that the exchange 
rate has an impact on the trade imbalance." In this way, the BOJ 
is saying that it is impossible to introduce the objective 
criteria. 
  The President's remark implicitly indicates his intention to 
induce Japan's concession by hinting at the possibility of using 
the card called "inducing sharp appreciation of the yen" once 
again because the Japan-U.S. summit talks failed to produce any 
progress. Officially, the government and the BOJ are faking 
calm, saying that it is also undesirable for the United States 
to incite further increase in the yen's value against the dollar 
because it will eventually lead to "a rise in long-term interest 
rates in the United States." However, a further increase in 
yen's value will also decrease business confidence and might 
negate the effect of the economic stimulus package. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

