<H3> <TI>   Source: Government To Back DPRK Sanctions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1102042394 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 10 
Feb 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1102042394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 10 February Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] With regard to the issue of suspected nuclear arms 
development by the DPRK (North Korea), a government source said 
on the morning of 10 February: "If no progress is made at the 
negotiations, there will be no other choice but to launch 
economic sanctions." Thus, he disclosed his view that if North 
Korea should keep on refusing nuclear inspections requested by 
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), economic 
sanctions by the UN Security Council would become unavoidable. 
As for the Japanese Government's actions if the UN Security 
Council's decides to adopt economic sanctions, the same source 
said: "As far as Japan is concerned, there is no other choice 
but to cooperate. In other words, we will do our utmost within 
the framework of the Constitution." 

</TEXT>

