<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MOFA Supports PRC Bid for GATT Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002145494 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 7 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1002145494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] China intends to join the General Agreement on 
Tariffs and Trade (GATT) within this year. The Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs [MOFA] positively supports this plan and is 
moving to call on the international community to "let China join 
it at an early date." This is because the MOFA has judged that 
"incorporating China into the framework of a market economy will 
eventually promote its reform." Japan also plans to take the 
initiative in holding bilateral tariff talks with China, which 
are preliminary steps to joining GATT, and appeal for "speeding 
up the procedures for China's admission" at the GATT's Uruguay 
Round ministerial conference to be held in Marrakech, Morocco, 
in April for signing the accord. 
  The current situation indicates that the World Trade 
Organization (WTO) will likely be inaugurated six months ahead 
of the original schedule. An accord was reached at the Uruguay 
Round talks that GATT will be changed into WTO in July 1995. It 
is with this background that Japan has started assisting China's 
early admission. If China should fail to obtain GATT membership 
within this year, it will also fail to become a founding WTO 
member. Then, China will have to once again start its 
application for the WTO membership after its inauguration. In 
this case, it is most likely that China's participation will be 
further delayed. 
  A senior MOFA official expressed his concern, and said: "If 
China is kept out of the WTO, the multinational rules in world 
trade will not be perfect." Moreover, the MOFA aims at 
indirectly checking the United States by having China admitted 
into the WTO system. 
  In a bid to win the membership before the year ends, China 
has been engaged in improving its trade conditions at home. For 
example, the dual exchange rates for the yuan were unified into 
one early this year. In March, GATT will hold working-level 
panel meetings on China's participation. However, in connection 
with the issue of renewal of the most-favored-nation status for 
China, the United Stated has indicated a cautious stance on 
China's GATT admission. Thus, if the current state is left 
unchanged, China may face a delicate situation regarding its 
GATT participation within this year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

