<H3> <TI>   Defense Chief Seeks 1.6 Percent Budget Increase </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0402132394 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 4 Feb 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0402132394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 3 February, Defense Agency [DA] Director General 
Kazuo Aichi met with Prime Minister Hosokawa at the prime 
minister's official residence. At the meeting, Aichi touched on 
the issue of the defense budget for fiscal 1994 and demanded 
that expenses be approved as requested in the roughly estimated 
budget demand. Director General Aichi said: "The roughly 
estimated budget demand calls for a 1.95 percent increase 
compared to the DA budget for fiscal 1993. However, we can keep 
it down to about a 1.6 percent increase if we look closely into 
the contents, including the foreign exchange rate. I hope it 
will not be trimmed more than that because further reduction 
will affect training and other matters." 
  Moreover, Ko Nakai, deputy secretary general of the Social 
Democratic Party, also met with Prime Minister Hosokawa on the 
same day at the prime minister's official residence. Nakai 
handed over a request, which calls for the approval of the 1994 
DA budget's full amount while giving considerations to defense 
industries, to the prime minister. 

</TEXT>

