<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK `Turned Cold' on N-S Economic Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1302035294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0325 GMT 13 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1302035294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 13 (YONHAP) -- As tension mounts over 
the matter of accepting international nuclear inspections, North 
Korea turned cold on inter-Korean economic cooperation which it 
has previously actively sought through unofficial channels, a 
government official said Sunday. 
  North Korean businessmen have lost interest in contacting 
their South Korean partners this year and instead are turning to 
American or Japanese firms to pursue joint-venture projects, the 
official said. 
  The change in their position is understood to be in 
connection with the dismissal of reform-minded Kim Tal-hyon as a 
vice premier and chairman of State Planning Commission and the 
mounting tension over the nuclear issue, the official said. 
  South and North Korean businessmen have continued their 
contacts in Beijing even when the nuclear problem became an 
international issue, he said, but the North is making no efforts 
this year. 
  Pyongyang is also very cold on allowing South Korean 
companies taking part in its infrastructure projects and instead 
is seeking partnership with U.S. or Japanese firms, he said. 
  Kim of North Korea reportedly met with Samsung, 
Lucky-Goldstar, Daewoo leaders in December 1992 and asked for 
their participation in Pyongyang's economic development projects. 

</TEXT>

