<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Reportedly Asks ROK To Invest in Port </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1502062194 Seoul CHOSON ILBO in Korean 15 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> SK1502062194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHOSON ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Yu Sung-u] </F>
  [Summary] North Korea has reportedly requested that ROK 
businesses invest capital into the development of Port Chongjin 
and is preparing for increased North-South trade by opening, 
within this year, a sea route between Chongjin and Pusan that is 
to serve twice a week. 
  According to authorities concerned on 14 February, Chairman 
Li Tiehu of the Xianhu business group of Jilin Province, China, 
visited the ROK in early February to discuss this issue and 
conveyed the North Korean authorities' intention that "Rather 
than China or any other country, North Korea is now counting on 
the South Korean side for the necessary funds to develop Port 
Chongjin that is estimated to exceed $100 million," and added 
that "North Korea is gearing up efforts to open sea routes 
between Pusan and Chongjin, and Inchon and Nampo as part of a 
plan to devote all of Chongjin to free economic zones." [Citing 
a Chinese source, Seoul HANGUK ILBO in Korean on 15 February 
1994 p 7 adds: "North Korea reportedly launched a feasibility 
study on opening Chongjin and Nampo as economic zones" and 
"North Korea once reviewed opening Sinuiju as an economic zone, 
only to withhold a final decision."] 
  Xianhu Business has been learned to have signed an exclusive 
contract with the North Hamgyong Provincial Administrative and 
Economic Committee, and the Economic Cooperation Co. of North 
Korea to build a wharf for containers and cranes, a road 
connecting Chongjin and Horyong, and to expand an open storage 
yard to 237,000 sq. yds. 

</TEXT>

