<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DP To Send Letter to Clinton on Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1502081694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0719 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1502081694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 15 (YONHAP) -- The opposition 
Democratic Party resolved at a caucus on Tuesday to send U.S. 
President Bill Clinton a letter urging a peaceful solution to 
the North Korean nuclear problem. 
  International sanctions against the Stalinist state would 
heighten tensions on the Korean peninsula, the main opposition 
party concluded at the meeting attended by supreme councilors 
and lawmakers belonging to the National Assembly's Defense and 
Foreign Affairs-National Unification Committees. 
  The letter will be delivered to Clinton, via Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher, by Rep. Chong Tae-chol when he visits 
Washington later this week. 
  The party also agreed that if sanctions become inevitable 
after the International Atomic Energy Agency's Board of 
Governors meeting slated for Feb. 21, they should be taken on a 
step-by-step basis. 
  Spokesman Pak Chi-won said the letter would convey to 
President Clinton the party's hope for fresh efforts to seek a 
peaceful way out, such as a package solution, by calming down 
U.S. hard-liners warning of the danger of war on the Korean 
peninsula. 

</TEXT>

