<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Official Urges Legal Service Market Opening </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1402015794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0140 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1402015794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 14 (YONHAP) -- The U.S. State Department 
has notified Seoul that it will take up the question of opening 
the South Korean market for foreign legal service at the third 
round of U.S.-South Korea Dialogue for Economic Cooperation 
(DEC) in Washington on Wednesday, the Justice Ministry said 
Monday. 
  The official letter, sent in the name of the assistant 
secretary of state, said that foreign legal service is needed in 
South Korea in order to protect U.S. interests as an increasing 
number of American companies are investing in Korea, according 
to Justice Ministry officials. 
  Kim Yong-chol, a specialist on international law at the 
Ministry, said, however, that Seoul should tell the U.S. side 
that the market cannot be opened since legal service in Korea, 
which works basically for the benefit of the public rather than 
individuals, has fundamentally different characteristics from 
that of the United States. 

</TEXT>

