<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia May Repay Loans With Armaments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1502020594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0155 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1502020594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, Feb. 15 (YONHAP) -- South Korea is 
positively considering a Russian offer to repay loans totaling 
1.47 billion U.S. dollars in the form of state-of-the-art 
weapons, not in cash, it was learned here on Monday. 
  The Seoul Government, having already examined two lists of 
arms Russia recently offered, has concluded that some would be 
useful in evaluating North Korea's weapons systems because they 
follow those of the former Soviet Union, informed sources here 
said. But Seoul would reject many others on the lists 
considering that its weapons systems are patterned after U.S. 
systems and that it maintains close relations with Washington, 
they added. 
  In response to Russia's proposal, Seoul will shortly send a 
group of weapons specialists to Moscow to study any technical 
problems with the arms and negotiate the terms of receiving them 
in place of the defaulted loans. 
  The Russian Army Chief of General Staff, Mikhail Kolesnikov, 
will visit Seoul in march to meet with Korean defense officials 
to discuss Russia's offer of weapons in payment for outstanding 
loans. 
  Russian Deputy Defense Minister Andrey Kokoshin said in a 
recent interview with YONHAP that Moscow is ready not only to 
offer many of its state-of-the-art weapons in payment for South 
Korean loans in arrears, but also to introduce Korean capital 
and marketing techniques in privatizing the Russian defense 
industry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

