<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tours of Overseas Nuclear Plants To Expand </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1402030694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0247 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1402030694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Feb. 14 (YONHAP) -- The government plans to 
expand overseas tours by political, educational and regional 
figures to observe nuclear power plants in an effort to promote 
the plants here, the Trade, Industry and Energy Ministry said on 
Monday. 
  Ministry officials said that additional construction of 
nuclear power plants in South Korea is inevitable, but that 
recognition of the situation and knowledge of nuclear reactors 
among the general public are inadequate. In a plan to enhance 
such recognition and knowledge, the Ministry will send 210 
people in 17 observation parties to overseas power plants this 
year, compared to 65 in eight parties last year. 
  The Ministry plans to construct 76 power plants including 14 
nuclear plants by 2006 to meet the demand for power, which is 
expected to increase by more than 10 percent yearly into the 
early 21st century. The plan will raise the proportion of 
nuclear power in electricity generation to 47.7 percent in 2006 
from the current 40.3 percent, Ministry officials explained. 

</TEXT>

