<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Canberra Not To Take Sides in U.S. `Trade War' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1502064494 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
15 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1502064494 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Paul Keating says Canberra will 
refuse to take sides in any trade war between Japan and the 
United States. Mr. Keating repeated that Australia would not 
enter any bilateral arrangements that were detrimental to Japan, 
but said this was different to taking sides. He said the 
tension between Tokyo and Washington reflected fundamental 
underlying differences. 
  [Begin Keating recording] The U.S. and Japan will work that 
out. We shall create a new institution to work it out within, 
and that is APEC [Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]. APEC 
gives the United States and Japan a chance within an umbrella 
organization to look at their policy and trade differences, but 
they will always do it bilaterally as well as in any other 
framework. 
  There is a lot of serious thought about this relationship, 
and it is in terms of their current account -- that has had a 
problem for years -- and this tension underlines the savings 
imbalance between the two countries. Now, it is going to take 
time to work this out, but it is working itself out in the sense 
now that the United States is enjoying very rapid growth of 
exports into North and South Asia. So the dependency of Japan 
upon the U.S. as a market is diminishing and, like most 
problems, they tend naturally to work themselves out. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

